AIM: 
To write a C program to demonstrate pointer arithmetic and accessing array elements using 
pointers. 
 
 
ALGORITHM: 
1. Start the program. 
2. Declare an integer array arr with some elements. 
3. Declare an integer pointer ptr and make it point to the first element of the array. 
4. Use pointer arithmetic to access array elements: 
 -> *(ptr + i) to get the value at index i. 
5. Demonstrate incrementing the pointer (ptr++) to move to the next element. 
6. Display all array elements using pointer arithmetic. 
7. Stop the program. 
 
 
PROGRAM: 
#include <stdio.h> 
int main() { 
int arr[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50}; 
int *ptr; 
int i; 
ptr = arr; // Pointer points to first element of array 
printf("Accessing array elements using pointer arithmetic:\n"); 
for (i = 0; i < 5; i++) { 
printf("Element %d: %d\n", i, *(ptr + i)); 
} 
printf("\nAccessing array elements by incrementing pointer:\n"); 
ptr = arr; // Reset pointer to first element 
for (i = 0; i < 5; i++) { 
printf("Element %d: %d\n", i, *ptr); 
ptr++; // Move pointer to next element 
} 
return 0; 
} 
 
 
 
SAMPLE OUTPUT: 
